The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 London, Oct. 3 (PTI): A 28-year-old non-resident Indian has been jailed for 27 years for conspiring to kidnap a fellow Indian and blackmail his father who lives in Gujarat.           
	Dipesh Kumar Chauhan, along with his accomplices Shujah Khaliq and Arif Aga, both aged 26, pleaded guilty during the two-week trial. They were sentenced to 18 years each in prison. Police did not name the victim.                  
	 Thekkady (Kerala) (PTI): The toll in the Thekkady tourist boat tragedy rose to 44 on Saturday with the recovery of the bodies of two children and a woman. Search is continuing in the lake as all persons who boarded the boat have not been accounted for so far.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): A Delhi court has refused to withdraw an order asking Samajwadi Party leader Amar Singh to pay Rs 5,000 for his failure to depose in a two-year-old cheating case filed by him. The court, however, allowed an application filed by Singhs counsel seeking exemption from personal appearance on Saturday on health grounds.                  
	 Bhopal (PTI): Madhya Pradesh police have arrested an RSS worker for killing his colleague during a shastra puja (weapon worship) organised by the RSS on Vijayadashmi. Naresh Motwani was killed when a pistol Shyamlal Gurjar was taking out of his pocket went off. The arrested Gurjar said it was an accident.                  
	 Jammu (PTI): A Pakistani national has been jailed for life for an explosion in a bus that killed 10 pilgrims 15 years ago. On November 28, 1994, Sonaullah planted a bomb in a bus bound for Katra, according to the prosecution.                  
	 Chennai (PTI): Home minister P. Chidambaram has said the Centre would look into a request by Tamil Nadu chief minister M. Karunanidhi to grant Indian citizenship to Sri Lankan Tamil refugees living in the state.                                                                                                                           
